cs.CL, cs.IR, cs.LG, cs.DB, cs.AI. 

The paper deals with the problem of jointly training structured models for extraction from multiple web sources, which involves natural language processing (NLP) and information retrieval (IR) techniques. Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) and cs.IR (Information Retrieval) are the most likely sub-categories. The paper also proposes a learning framework that involves biasing models to agree on shared text segments, which can be seen as a machine learning (ML) problem. Hence, cs.LG (Machine Learning) is also a likely sub-category. Additionally, the paper deals with extracting data from web sources, which involves database (DB) techniques. Therefore, cs.DB is another likely sub-category. Finally, the paper proposes a scheme to discover low-noise agreement regions in unlabeled data, which can be seen as an AI problem. Hence, cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is also a likely sub-category.
